{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526790"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:25:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:25:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14155"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14155"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.17,0.04,0.2,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6838"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103649"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6838"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86066"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5495"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36587"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103649"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her family, including her husband and two children aged five and eight years. They have all experienced a 24-hour episode of vomiting and diarrhoea after eating a meal prepared at home two days ago. The meal included roast chicken, salad, and rice. They are now recovering and maintaining adequate hydration. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She asks for advice on preventing similar incidents in the future.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following food safety measures would be most effective in preventing future episodes of foodborne gastroenteritis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Washing hands thoroughly before and after handling raw foods","Refrigerating all leftovers within four hours of cooking","Washing raw chicken prior to food preparation","Cooking all meats until well-done, regardless of personal preference","Washing fruits and vegetables with soap before consumption"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis family experienced a typical episode of foodborne gastroenteritis, likely due to contamination during food preparation. The most effective single intervention to prevent future episodes is proper hand hygiene.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWashing hands thoroughly before and after handling raw foods\u003C/strong\u003E is the most critical food safety measure. Hand contamination is the primary vector for transferring pathogens from raw foods to ready-to-eat items, cooking surfaces, and utensils. This practice addresses the root cause of most cross-contamination events during food preparation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefrigerating all leftovers within four hours of cooking\u003C/strong\u003E helps prevent bacterial multiplication in cooked foods, but the standard recommendation is actually within two hours. More importantly, this measure does not address the initial contamination that likely occurred during preparation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWashing raw chicken prior to food preparation\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended and can actually increase contamination risk. This practice spreads pathogens around the kitchen through splashing and does not reduce the bacterial load on the chicken itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECooking all meats until well-done, regardless of personal preference\u003C/strong\u003E is overly restrictive. While cooking meats to safe internal temperatures is important, using a food thermometer to ensure appropriate temperatures is more practical than insisting on well-done preparation for all dishes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWashing fruits and vegetables with soap before consumption\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for home food preparation. While fruits and vegetables should be rinsed with clean water, using soap can leave harmful residues and is unnecessary for removing pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEffective food safety requires a comprehensive approach, but hand hygiene remains the cornerstone of prevention as it addresses the most common pathway for pathogen transmission during food preparation and handling. Other important food safety practices include cooking foods to safe internal temperatures, keeping raw and cooked foods separate, refrigerating perishable foods promptly, and avoiding preparing food when ill.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hand hygiene is the single most effective measure in preventing transmission of gastroenteritis and foodborne pathogens.","Cross-contamination between raw and cooked foods is a major cause of foodborne illness outbreaks.","Proper food storage temperatures and timing are critical but secondary to preventing initial contamination."],"references":["Lee M, Greig JD. A review of nosocomial Salmonella outbreaks: infection control interventions found effective. Public Health 2013; 127:199-206.","Food Standards. 2023. Food safety basics. https://www.foodstandards.gov.au/consumer/prevention-of-foodborne-illness/food-safety-basics. Accessed 25/05/2025"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86066"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14155"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86066"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T13:42:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T13:43:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6838"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103649"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":